## What this is

This is a Direction: the call has been made, the ends are settled, and you are not here to argue whether to make it. The means are open and yours to work out. The why above is the specification; if it also lists where the change should be made, that sweep is one fallible sketch written before the work was understood; where it and the why disagree, the why wins.

{% if signed_off %}The operator has signed off on this Direction: they have seen the call and agree its framing represents what they meant to be discussing, so you start from a shared picture. The ends are settled by the kind, not by their sign-off, and signing is not their judgement that the call is right; the hinge below is still where it can come apart.{% else %}No one has put their name to this Direction: an agent most likely made the call from a request for something related, and the operator may never have seen it. The ends are settled by the kind all the same, but the call is the author's and unvouched, so press the hinge below hard; it is where the call comes apart in your hands.{% endif %}

One assumption carries the call: the hinge, the thing whose failure would change what the call even becomes. It is the one place the settled ends could still turn out wrong, and it is what your check-in is for.

## What to do

**1.** Claim it: `vv assignment-claim {{ assignment_id }}`.

**2.** Rebuild the work from the why before you write. Don't start from the listed sweep: say what would have to be true for this call to be right, derive what actually has to change from that, then check that against the sweep; where they disagree, the sweep is wrong, not your derivation. Lean on the hinge where being wrong about it would cost the most, often a neighbouring context that holds a different theory of this work; confirming it against your own code only ratifies it. This is your work: do it, don't narrate it.

**3.** Now write the check-in, and for this turn be the operator reading it, not the agent who did the work. You are running ten to twenty assignments like this one at once, each competing for your zero-sum attention, all serving one coherent Project, and you have seconds for this one before the next is waiting. You scan the bold lead of each item and read into the body under it only when a lead stops you, so the whole of what you must decide has to live in the leads. Open by naming the assignment: that it is a Direction and what its call is, in the domain's own words as if to someone who has never seen it, before any finding. This is a hard rule, not one keep among several: a hinge verdict lands on no one who does not yet hold what call it is the hinge of. Then draft the rest as the check-in you would want handed to you, and read it back from that seat and cut every line that would not change what you do next, every line there only to show you the work got done. The report that you grounded, or rebuilt the means, or that a check-in follows, is the first to go. What survives, lead with its conclusion in the bold opening of its line — the verdict, the call — never the question it answers and never the ground it stands on, which follows after, in a line at most: the hinge, whether it held or gave and if it gave what the call becomes, as a claim that can fall ("the call rests on X; if X is false it is no longer this but that"); and the shape of the means you derived. Then black out all but those bold openings and read what is left: a call you must make that is not there has not reached the operator, and you lift it into the opening rather than add a line to point at it. Leave the goal itself alone; the ends are decided. Then wait.

